  { name: "Mare Tranquillitatis", lat: 8.5, lon: 31.4, size: 873, description: "Mare Tranquillitatis (Sea of Tranquility) is a 873-km-diameter mare on the Moon's near side, forever famous as the site of humanity's first crewed lunar landing when Apollo 11 touched down on July 20, 1969. The mare occupies an ancient impact basin formed during the pre-Nectarian period (over 4 billion years ago) that was subsequently flooded by basaltic lava flows approximately 3.6-3.8 billion years ago. The basalts are relatively high in titanium (high-Ti basalts with 10-13% TiO₂), giving parts of the mare a bluish tint in enhanced color images. The mare's smooth, relatively flat surface made it ideal for Apollo landings—in addition to Apollo 11, Ranger 8 impacted here and Surveyor 5 landed successfully. The lunar samples returned by Apollo 11 from Tranquillitatis provided the first direct evidence of lunar volcanism and revealed the mare's age and composition. The mare is bordered by rugged highlands to the south and connects to Mare Serenitatis to the north, forming part of the interconnected near-side mare system.", mass: "", link: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mare_Tranquillitatis" },
  { name: "Mare Serenitatis", lat: 28.0, lon: 17.5, size: 707, description: "Mare Serenitatis (Sea of Serenity) is a 707-km-diameter circular mare formed within one of the Moon's major impact basins, created by a massive impact about 3.9 billion years ago during the Nectarian period. The basin was subsequently flooded by basaltic lava flows between 3.8 and 3.7 billion years ago, forming the smooth dark surface visible today. The mare exhibits a distinct color difference between its western and eastern portions due to variations in titanium content and age of different lava flows. Serenitatis is surrounded by spectacular mountain ranges including the Montes Haemus to the south and Montes Caucasus to the east, which are remnants of the basin's original rim uplifted during the impact. The Taurus-Littrow valley on the southeastern edge was the Apollo 17 landing site. The mare contains several interesting features including Posidonius crater on its northeastern rim and numerous wrinkle ridges (dorsa) formed by compression of the cooling lava. GRAIL gravity measurements revealed that Serenitatis has one of the most pronounced mascons (mass concentrations) on the Moon, indicating dense lava fill and mantle uplift beneath the basin.", mass: "", link: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mare_Serenitatis" },
  { name: "Mare Crisium", lat: 17.0, lon: 59.1, size: 418, description: "Mare Crisium (Sea of Crises) is a distinctive 418-km-diameter oval-shaped mare near the northeastern limb of the Moon's near side, appearing foreshortened from Earth. The mare occupies an impact basin formed during the Nectarian period around 3.9 billion years ago, with lava flooding occurring 3.3-3.0 billion years ago—relatively young compared to most maria. Crisium is geologically isolated from the other nearside maria, separated by highland terrain, making it an important independent sample of lunar volcanism. The mare is actually circular, but appears elongated east-west when viewed from Earth due to perspective; it's approximately 570 km in the north-south direction and 420 km east-west. The basin has a pronounced mascon indicating substantial lava fill and crustal thinning. Luna 15 crashed here during a sample return attempt, Luna 24 successfully returned samples in 1976, and Blue Ghost Mission 1 landed in 2025. The relatively young age and isolated nature of Crisium make its basalts chemically distinct from other maria, and the Soviet Luna 24 samples revealed unique compositions not found elsewhere.", mass: "", link: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mare_Crisium" },
  { name: "Mare Imbrium", lat: 32.8, lon: -15.6, size: 1145, description: "Mare Imbrium (Sea of Rains) is the largest impact basin on the Moon's near side with a diameter of approximately 1,145 km (some measurements extend to 1,300 km including outer rings). The basin formed from a cataclysmic impact about 3.9 billion years ago during the late heavy bombardment, excavating material from deep within the Moon and creating ejecta deposits across the entire near side. The impact was so massive it created concentric mountain rings including the spectacular Montes Apenninus, Montes Carpatus, and Montes Caucasus that rise 3-6 km above the mare floor. Subsequent volcanic flooding occurred in multiple episodes from 3.8 to 2.0 billion years ago, with younger flows in the center. The mare basalts vary in composition, age, and titanium content across different regions. Imbrium hosted multiple exploration missions including Luna 17/Lunokhod 1, Apollo 15 at Hadley-Apennine, and Chang'e 3/Yutu. The basin's formation was a defining event in lunar history, and its ejecta (Fra Mauro formation) was sampled by Apollo 14. Imbrium shows classic mare features including wrinkle ridges, sinuous rilles, ghost craters, and young impact craters like Copernicus whose rays stretch across the mare surface.", mass: "", link: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mare_Imbrium" },
  { name: "Oceanus Procellarum", lat: 18.4, lon: -57.4, size: 2568, description: "Oceanus Procellarum (Ocean of Storms) is the largest mare feature on the Moon, spanning approximately 2,568 km and covering roughly 4 million square kilometers of the western near side. Unlike most maria which occupy circular impact basins, Procellarum has an irregular shape and may not be impact-origin at all—current theories suggest it formed above an ancient region of volcanic activity driven by heat-producing radioactive elements (the Procellarum KREEP Terrane). The 'ocean' was filled by numerous volcanic eruption episodes spanning from 3.8 billion to possibly as recent as 1.2 billion years ago, making it one of the longest-lived volcanic regions on the Moon. The basalts are generally lower in titanium than Mare Tranquillitatis but show extreme diversity. Procellarum contains the highest concentrations of thorium, uranium, and potassium on the Moon, along with rare earth elements. Multiple missions have landed here including Surveyor 1, Surveyor 3, Apollo 12, Luna 9, and Chang'e 5. The mare contains spectacular features including Aristarchus Plateau (the brightest region on the Moon), numerous sinuous rilles indicating lava channels, and extensive wrinkle ridge systems. Recent discoveries suggest Procellarum formed above an ancient rift system in the lunar crust.", mass: "", link: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oceanus_Procellarum" },
  { name: "Mare Nubium", lat: -21.3, lon: -16.6, size: 715, description: "Mare Nubium (Sea of Clouds) is a 715-km-diameter mare in the southern near side, occupying a pre-Nectarian impact basin over 4.1 billion years old that was flooded by basaltic lavas approximately 3.6-3.0 billion years ago. The mare is notable for its irregular shape and connections to other maria including Oceanus Procellarum to the west. Nubium exhibits extensive wrinkle ridges (dorsa) indicating compression of the cooling lava flows, and its western part contains the Rupes Recta (Straight Wall)—a 110-km-long fault scarp rising about 300 meters, one of the most prominent tectonic features on the near side. The mare basalts have moderate to low titanium content and show color variations indicating different ages and compositions of lava flows. The region is particularly enriched in KREEP materials (potassium, rare earth elements, and phosphorus), making it geochemically significant. Several spacecraft have impacted in or near Nubium including Ranger 9 which targeted Alphonsus crater on the eastern edge, and Luna 5. The mare's position between highlands makes it valuable for studying the transition from ancient crustal material to volcanic mare deposits.", mass: "", link: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mare_Nubium" },
  { name: "Mare Humorum", lat: -24.4, lon: -38.6, size: 389, description: "Mare Humorum (Sea of Moisture) is a nearly circular 389-km-diameter mare occupying an impact basin formed during the Nectarian period about 3.9 billion years ago, with volcanic flooding occurring 3.5-3.3 billion years ago. The mare is notable for its well-preserved circular shape and pronounced mascon (mass concentration) indicating substantial lava fill—GRAIL measurements show it has one of the strongest positive gravity anomalies on the Moon. The basin is surrounded by concentric ring structures including rugged mountainous terrain and radial fractures extending outward. The mare floor is relatively smooth with moderate-titanium basalts and shows numerous wrinkle ridges concentric to the basin rim, formed by subsidence and compression. A system of rilles and faults surrounds the mare, particularly prominent on the western side. Humorum is located in the southwestern near side, west of Mare Nubium, and is bordered by several prominent craters including Gassendi on its northern rim. No missions have landed directly in Humorum, but it has been extensively studied by orbital missions for its classic basin structure and dense lava fill, which provides insights into lunar volcanic processes and basin formation mechanics.", mass: "", link: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mare_Humorum" },
  { name: "Mare Fecunditatis", lat: -7.8, lon: 51.3, size: 909, description: "Mare Fecunditatis (Sea of Fertility) is a 909-km-diameter mare in the eastern near side, occupying one of the oldest recognizable impact basins on the Moon, formed during the pre-Nectarian period over 4.0 billion years ago. The basin was subsequently flooded by basaltic lavas in multiple episodes from 3.9 to 3.0 billion years ago, with the oldest mare basalts potentially representing some of the earliest lunar volcanism. The mare has an irregular shape and merges with Mare Tranquillitatis to the northwest and Mare Nectaris to the southwest. Fecunditatis basalts are relatively low in titanium and show color variations indicating different ages and compositions. The mare is surrounded by rugged highlands including the prominent crater Langrenus on its eastern rim. Luna 16 successfully returned samples from the southwestern edge in 1970—the first robotic sample return—retrieving 101 grams of material. The mare contains several interesting features including dorsa (wrinkle ridges), small craters, and irregular mare patches. The ancient basin and varied lava ages make Fecunditatis important for understanding the early volcanic history of the Moon and the duration of mare volcanism.", mass: "", link: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mare_Fecunditatis" },
  { name: "Mare Nectaris", lat: -15.2, lon: 35.5, size: 333, description: "Mare Nectaris (Sea of Nectar) is a relatively small 333-km-diameter circular mare that occupies one of the most well-preserved multi-ring impact basins on the Moon. The Nectaris basin formed about 3.92 billion years ago during the Nectarian period (which is named after this basin), and its formation is used as a key time marker in lunar stratigraphy. The basin shows at least three distinct concentric rings including the inner mare-filled basin, an intermediate ring now partly buried, and the outer Altai Scarp (Rupes Altai)—a spectacular 480-km-diameter ring mountain that rises 1-2 km and represents the basin's main rim. The mare was flooded by basaltic lavas approximately 3.7-3.2 billion years ago. Surveyor 5 successfully landed on the mare in 1967 and conducted the first chemical analysis of lunar soil. The prominent crater Theophilus sits on the northeastern rim, having formed after the mare filling. Nectaris basalts are relatively low in titanium, and the mare shows the classic features of a well-preserved impact basin including radial fractures, concentric structures, and basin ejecta extending hundreds of kilometers outward.", mass: "", link: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mare_Nectaris" },
  { name: "Mare Frigoris", lat: 56.0, lon: 1.4, size: 1596, description: "Mare Frigoris (Sea of Cold) is a long, irregular mare extending approximately 1,596 km in the east-west direction across the northern near side of the Moon, making it one of the most elongated mare features. Unlike most circular maria that occupy impact basins, Frigoris has a complex, irregular shape suggesting formation through a combination of processes including possible basin filling, volcanic flooding of interconnected lowlands, or filling of ancient rift valleys. The mare lies at high northern latitude (around 56°N), giving it its name due to the perception of coldness associated with the polar regions. Volcanic activity filled Frigoris between 3.8 and 2.0 billion years ago with multiple episodes creating basalts of varying ages and compositions. The mare serves as a boundary between the heavily cratered northern highlands and the smoother terrain to the south, and it partially surrounds the crater Plato on its southern edge. Hakuto-R Mission 2 crashed in this region during its landing attempt in 2025. The irregular nature and extended formation history make Frigoris valuable for understanding how volcanic flooding occurred in non-basin settings and the distribution of late-stage lunar volcanism.", mass: "", link: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mare_Frigoris" },
  { name: "Mare Vaporum", lat: 13.3, lon: 3.6, size: 245, description: "Mare Vaporum (Sea of Vapors) is a small, irregular mare approximately 245 km across, located on the near side between Mare Serenitatis to the northeast and Sinus Medii to the south. The mare lies along the lunar central meridian (0° longitude), making it a prominent feature when the Moon is viewed from Earth at certain phases. Vaporum does not occupy a well-defined impact basin; instead, it appears to fill an irregular depression or possibly represents volcanic flooding of a degraded ancient basin. The basaltic lavas that form the mare were emplaced approximately 3.6-3.4 billion years ago and are relatively low in titanium. The western edge of the mare features the striking Hyginus Rille, a linear graben or collapsed lava tube system with crater-like pits along its length. The mare is bounded by highlands including the Haemus Mountains to the north (part of the Serenitatis basin rim). No missions have landed in Mare Vaporum, but its position near the center of the near side has made it a frequent target for telescopic observation and orbital photography. The mare's small size and irregular shape provide insights into localized volcanic activity outside the major basin systems.", mass: "", link: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mare_Vaporum" },
  { name: "Sinus Medii", lat: 2.4, lon: -1.0, size: 335, description: "Sinus Medii (Central Bay) is a small mare feature approximately 335 km in extent, located at nearly the exact center point of the Moon's near side (very close to 0°N, 0°E). This central location makes it one of the first features visible as the Moon transitions from new to first quarter phase, and it was historically used as the origin point for lunar coordinate systems. Sinus Medii is not a true mare in the sense of occupying a defined impact basin; rather, it consists of irregular patches of basaltic material filling low-lying areas and connecting larger maria including Mare Vaporum to the north and Oceanus Procellarum to the west. The volcanic flooding occurred approximately 3.3 billion years ago, relatively late in lunar volcanic history. Surveyor 6 landed near Sinus Medii in November 1967 and became famous for performing the first rocket liftoff from the lunar surface. The region contains several notable craters including Rhaeticus and Triesnecker (with its extensive rille system). The central location and mix of highland and mare materials make Sinus Medii useful for studying the transition between lunar crustal types and understanding how isolated volcanic deposits formed outside major basins.", mass: "", link: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sinus_Medii" }
